<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
    Hardened Runtime carve-outs required by Tauri's WKWebView.
    Hardened Runtime is enabled by default for notarized Developer ID
    apps (via `codesign --options runtime`, applied automatically by
    `tauri build`), and these carve-outs let the embedded webview do
    JIT + dynamic linking without breaking the notarization check.

    App Sandbox (`com.apple.security.app-sandbox`) is intentionally
    ABSENT. Sandbox is mandatory for Mac App Store apps; optional for
    Developer ID distribution (which we use via peoplepartner.io).
    Enabling it would cause the Tauri auto-updater to fail silently:
    kernel sandbox blocks `file-write-unlink` on the app's own bundle
    in /Applications, which the updater does as part of in-place
    replacement. Loss of sandbox isn't a threat-model regression —
    our defenses are Keychain (API keys), SQLite at rest (local data),
    and PII redaction at egress. Kernel-level file sandboxing wasn't
    load-bearing for any of those.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
